                'answerText' => 'The classic example is The Lord of the Rings; both the books and the movies are the gold standard to which all other high fantasy is compared. The Chronicles of Narnia is another classic high fantasy series. The Wheel of Time series is an ongoing high fantasy world, and Ursula K. Le Guin\'s Earthsea series and Terry Pratchett\'s Discworld books are both mold-breaking high fantasy works. Onscreen, the Willow movie and television show, The Neverending Story, the How to Train Your Dragon series, and Dungeons & Dragons: Honor Among Thieves are good examples. High fantasy video games are practically ubiquitous, with perhaps the most famous examples being The Legend of Zelda series, the Final Fantasy series, the Baldur\'s Gate games, the Elder Scrolls series, and the Dragon Age series.',
            ],
            3 => [
                'questionText' => 'Do I need to know about a high fantasy world before I play a game set there?',
                'answerText' => 'Generally, no! Very few game masters will expect you to be familiar with the lore and history of a fantastical world to play a game set in it. In fact, a majority of game masters actually make up their own fantasy worlds to play in when they run high fantasy games! They might give you some background information to help you make a character who fits in, but it\'s unreasonable to make players into scholars of imaginary worlds to qualify for playing RPGs there. 

That said, if you play in a fantasy world you DO happen to have an encyclopedic knowledge of, a sense of place and knowledge of that world can often enhance your experience immersing yourself as one of its denizens.',
            ],
