        'faqs' => [
            0 => [
                'questionText' => 'Can you play funny games online?',
                'answerText' => 'Yes! It\'s totally possible to play a comedy-focused funny RPG online. As virtual tabletops and voice/videoconferencing tools get better, it\'s easier than ever to feel like you and your fellow players are gathered around the table, laughing and joking together. In many cases, online platforms actually make games funnier, with digital soundboards, dedicated text and image channels for jokes and memes about what\'s happening in the game, and of course, drawing tools on virtual tabletops allowing players to graffiti the Big Bad Evil Guy\'s gothic castle.',
            ],
            1 => [
                'questionText' => 'What makes RPGs funny?',
                'answerText' => 'Some RPG rulebooks are funny on their own, with clever and hilarious writing. Some are designed to set up convoluted situations where players will make funny things happen naturally, no matter what they do. And some require players to perform actions that are silly or ridiculous as part of the rules of the game, getting everyone in on the joke and creating a comedic atmosphere.',
            ],
            2 => [
                'questionText' => 'Do I have to be funny to play a comedy game?',
                'answerText' => 'The beauty of well-designed comedy RPGs is that they don\'t rely on the comedic skills and timing of their players to be funny. While a funny player might embellish the natural situational comedy and crazy hijinks the game creates, great funny games allow any player to get huge laughs and be hilarious just by playing! You\'ll be amazed at just how naturally funny you are when you commit to a character and the premise of a silly game.',
            ],
            3 => [
                'questionText' => 'Do I need to do a funny voice when I play a TTRPG?',
                'answerText' => 'Actual play shows cast with professional voice actors and comedians can sometimes create an unrealistic expectation that RPG players need to be performers. In reality, while some players enjoy play-acting, doing voices and accents, and getting fully "into character," it\'s by no means necessary for great roleplay! Roleplay is all about making choices as your character. Silly voices are fun, but ultimately just embellishment on what really matters: being honest, playing hard, and being true to your character.',
            ],
