            0 => [
                'questionText' => 'What does "eldritch" mean?',
                'answerText' => '"Eldritch" comes from the same Old English root as the word "elf"! In this case, it refers to elves as the bogeymen of the British Isles; malevolent spirits that were thought to be the cause of curses, maladies, and anything strange or inexplicable. Today, we use the word to refer to sinister strangeness with no logical explanation, or something beyond human comprehension.',
            ],
            1 => [
                'questionText' => 'What\'s the difference between eldritch horror, cosmic horror, and Lovecraftian horror?',
                'answerText' => 'Generally, these three terms are synonymous, for the genre of horror, understood to have originated from the works of H. P. Lovecraft, that deals with forces so ancient, powerful, and incomprehensible that they dwarf and shatter human understanding. 

Some distinction can be drawn between them, where "eldritch horror" refers to fear of the uncanny or inexplicable; "cosmic horror" refers to fear of the enormity and age of the cosmos and things born from it, and the insignificance of humankind in comparison; and "Lovecraftian horror" refers specifically to the writings of the author and derivative work, especially the Cthulhu mythos. Note that some prefer to avoid "Lovecraftian horror" to de-center the author and his demonstrably bigoted views.',
            ],
            2 => [
                'questionText' => 'What are some examples of eldritch horror in media?',
                'answerText' => 'H. P. Lovecraft\'s Cthulhu mythos is considered the origin of the genre, so his books and short stories like The Call of Cthulhu and At the Mountains of Madness are central texts. Other stories like The King in Yellow, and House of Leaves are older and newer entries, respectively. The book and film Annihilation and the rest of The Southern Reach series deal with eldritch horror themes, as do movies like The Thing, Color Out of Space, and Event Horizon. On television, Lovecraft Country, Twin Peaks, the first season of True Detective, and the first episode of Chernobyl all share elements of the genre. Lastly, video games like Bloodborne, Dredge, Darkest Dungeon, Sunless Sea, and the Amnesia series all play in eldritch horror\'s particular kind of darkness.',
            ],
            3 => [
                'questionText' => 'What do you do in eldritch horror games?',
                'answerText' => 'Typically, players take on the role of investigators, whether independent or sent by a government. Often what starts as a seemingly normal mystery slowly reveals itself to be caused by supernatural or otherworldly forces. By convention of the genre, they are usually inexorably compelled by curiosity or self-destructive impulse to seek the truth of a case, even if learning it might drive them insane. By the time the eldritch elements have revealed themselves, it may already be too late. These entities and phenomena cannot be overcome by force, so investigators must get creative or be consumed by monstrous powers!',
            ],
            4 => [
                'questionText' => 'What is the relationship of sanity to eldritch horror?',
                'answerText' => 'Eldritch horror RPGs frequently track the deteriorating mental condition of the characters by measuring their sanity, or otherwise indicating how their exposure to eldritch forces has warped their perception of reality. 

