        'faqs' => [
            0 => [
                'questionText' => 'What kinds of apocalypses are there?',
                'answerText' => 'One of the most popular ways to end the world is zombies! Whether it\'s an infectious plague or some kind of magic, the rise of flesh-eating undead always has a way of showing up in popular media as a vehicle for societal collapse. There are also climate apocalypses, like Mad Max or Waterworld, which might be concurrent with nuclear apocalypses, which were especially common themes during the cold war. Apocalypses resulting from computers and machines turning against us like in The Matrix, Dune, Terminator, and lots more are also common. Less common but still prominent are alien invasions, natural disasters, or a divine prophetic "end of the world."',
            ],
            1 => [
                'questionText' => 'What are some examples of post-apocalyptic media?',
                'answerText' => 'The Mad Max series of films is probably the first apocalypse that jumps to most folks minds, but there are many others. The Walking Dead television show and comic books, The Last of Us video game and show, and the book and show Station Eleven are all recent and quite popular post-apocalyptic media. Movie franchises like The Matrix, the Terminator series, and any number of zombie apocalypse films give various views of an apocalyptic future. If it\'s books you\'re looking for, The Road, The Parable of the Sower, and War of the Worlds offer some visions. In video games, the Fallout and Horizon Zero Dawn series have you covered.',
            ],
            2 => [
                'questionText' => 'What are the themes of post-apocalyptic media?',
                'answerText' => 'The struggle against scarcity and the harshness of the natural environment are two common themes. Humans organizing into groups and clashing with other groups over limited resources is a dynamic post-apocalyptic media often embraces. The balance between the benefits of cooperation and the difficulty of sharing resources is a frequent tension. Wealth inequality and power disparity show up too, as more powerful forces hoard resources. The loss of knowledge and the decay of the social order often causes post-apocalyptic worlds to spiral into worse condition. But perhaps the central question of the genre is whether humanity, not just as a species, but as a concept, can survive the collapse of society; will we be able to hold onto our compassion, or will we become animals?',
            ],
            3 => [
                'questionText' => 'Are post-apocalyptic games depressing?',
                'answerText' => 'Not necessarily! While it could definitely feel like a bleak game if every session is fighting a constantly losing battle against scarcity and entropy, with only things getting worse, post-apocalyptic games are often downright hopeful about humanity\'s future. On one hand, yes, the world as we knew it has ended, and a great deal of life, knowledge, and resources have been lost. On the other, it is up to the survivors to rebuild a world that is better than it was. A daunting project, but far from a depressing one.',
            ],
        ],
