            0 => [
                'questionText' => 'What\'s the difference between science fiction and space opera?',
                'answerText' => 'Where science fiction grounds itself in existing or conceivable scientific knowledge to tell stories of humanity among the stars, space opera uses the trappings and setting of science fiction to tell grand, dramatic stories unconstrained by scientific reality. Space opera is often more melodramatic, more fantastical, and larger in scope and scale than science fiction. Spaceships zip between star systems at faster-than-light speeds, various species of aliens exist in metropolitan societies, and there might even be psionics or space magic as an element of the setting.',
            ],
            1 => [
                'questionText' => 'What are the tropes of space opera?',
                'answerText' => 'A galaxy-spanning force of evil, like a tyrannical empire or invasive alien species, against which the heroes struggle. A vast array of alien cultures and societies, occasionally with humanoid features, who coexist with humanity as it spreads throughout the stars. Some kind of psychic power or space magic which can be harnessed by a select few. Laser weaponry, both handheld and spaceship mounted, allowing for shootouts and dogfights. Romance and friendship blooming among the high drama of galactic warfare. Pirates, smugglers, and the seedy underbelly of respectable interstellar society. Desert planets and alien monsters. And of course, laser swords.',
            ],
            2 => [
                'questionText' => 'What are some examples of space opera media?',
                'answerText' => 'Star Wars is the 900-pound gorilla of space opera, taking inspiration from classic Flash Gordon serials and turning the genre into a multigenerational phenomenon. Virtually all space opera media is in conversation with Star Wars. Among those media are shows like Firefly and Cowboy Bebop, The Expanse novels and their television adaptation, and video games like Destiny and Mass Effect. Even the Star Trek series takes frequent dips into the space opera genre.

Frank Herbert\'s Dune series is one seminal work of space opera fiction that predates Star Wars, and in fact Herbert himself, among many others, have claimed that Dune was one of the inspirations for Star Wars!',
            ],
