    23 => [
        'slug' => 'low-magic',
        'name' => 'Low Magic',
        'description' => 'Low magic is a subgenre descriptor applied to another genre, usually fantasy, that indicates that magic is rare, subtle, or very costly. It\'s sometimes called "low fantasy" and concurrent with darker themes and a grittier tone, but not always. Low magic fiction might be set in our own world before magic was lost, or where magic struggles to survive in secret. It might be set in the far future after a technological collapse where "magic" is just fragments of still-functional technology. Or it might be a fantasy world where magic is dying, highly secretive and esoteric, or simply very difficult to perform.

Low magic tabletop roleplaying games limit players\' access to world-shaking, game-changing magical spells, or make such things the subject of entire adventures to achieve. This allows a fantastical world somewhat grounded in reality that makes magic feel rare and special. When magic does appear, it\'s a big deal! A low magic game makes healing difficult, so violence is costly, and players must solve problems with their wits and prowess rather than magic spells. For this reason, low magic games are often seen as more challenging to players.',
