        'faqs' => [
            0 => [
                'questionText' => 'What are some examples of low magic in media?',
                'answerText' => 'There are many examples in media of low magic worlds, where magic is either exceedingly rare or not particularly powerful. In Game of Thrones on television and A Song of Ice and Fire, the books from which it was adapted, magic only exists in the hands of a select few characters, and most people in that world never see it in their lives. While the Lord of the Rings books and films are high fantasy, in the world magic itself is slowly leaving, and actual magic spells and artifacts are increasingly rare. The world of The Witcher series is also relatively low-magic, although it appears frequently enough in the protagonist\'s adventures due to his profession. Arthurian-inspired film The Green Knight is a low magic narrative, and the television series Fargo includes at least one subtle supernatural element in every season. Similarly, in shows like Supernatural and Buffy, magic is limited in power, kept secret from ordinary people, and special when it appears.',
            ],
            1 => [
                'questionText' => 'Why should I play in a low magic setting?',
                'answerText' => 'If you want a more grounded world where magic exists, but feels special every time it comes up, you might enjoy low magic. In many games, proliferation of magical abilities makes magic the catch-all solution to every problem, leading to a stagnation in tactics and strategy, and making characters without magic feel less useful. In low magic systems, it might still be possible to solve problems with magic, but in a more limited and costly way. Similarly, it might create new and interesting challenges to deal with when characters must use their own strength, wits, and creativity to solve problems. And without magical healing, characters might think twice about getting into fights.',
            ],
            2 => [
                'questionText' => 'How does magic manifest in low magic settings?',
                'answerText' => 'There\'s no limit to the ways magic might show up, but there are some common threads. Sometimes, magic is not something people possess, but rather the ability to communicate with gods or spirits who are its actual source. It might only be accessible by arcane rituals or ancient artifacts into which the magic is imbued, and might require sacrifice or have a serious drawback or cost to its use. Magic might even be a limited resource, and every usage drains a little more magic from the world, causing it to slowly die out.',
            ],
            3 => [
                'questionText' => 'Is magic weak in low magic settings?',
                'answerText' => 'Not always! In many cases, magic is still a very powerful force. It may be weakening, or it may once have been stronger, but frequently low magic means magic is rare, rather than weak or useless. If you want to use magic in a low magic game, be prepared for it to be a limited resource or require work or sacrifice to use, though it may still be game-changing every time it\'s used. Part of the appeal of low magic is how special magic is when it does appear.',
            ],
            4 => [
                'questionText' => 'What\'s the difference between urban fantasy, low fantasy, and modern?',
                'answerText' => 'Urban fantasy is specifically a contemporary city setting with overt or covert fantasy elements. Modern fantasy has similar fantastical elements, but isn\'t necessarily set in a city. Low fantasy can be set in any time period, and indicates the fantastical elements are rare or secretive, though usually integrated into the setting. And the modern genre is simply set in the world as we know it now or relatively recently in the past or near in the future, with no assumption of fantasy elements at all.',
