            0 => [
                'questionText' => 'How do I know if a game system is universal?',
                'answerText' => 'If a game refers to itself as "universal" or "generic," that\'s usually a pretty good indicator, but if not, there are a few other ways to tell. A universal system won\'t make many assumptions about the setting, genre, or themes of the game it\'s being used to run. That usually means no classes, and skills will have broad, general names instead of specific ones. Rules will be modular, meaning they are optional and can easily add into or remove from a game without changing much else. It might have such modules for magic, combat, travel, modern technology, and more which can be slotted into a game that wants them.',
            ],
            1 => [
                'questionText' => 'Can a universal system do anything?',
                'answerText' => 'Yes, but there\'s a "but!" Universal systems function like toolboxes, giving players and game masters the tools to build a ruleset that will support the game they want to play. That means some of the work is on the players to produce the setting and theme they want, picking and choosing which tools to use. In some cases, the tools might not exist, or might exist in a separate supplementary rulebook, and the group will have to collect them or build them themselves.

Additionally, it\'s impossible to make a game that can truly do EVERYthing. Even universal systems admit there are some base assumptions, like "a game about competent people facing dramatic challenges," or "a game about human relationships." Just the fact that there exist multiple universal systems should tell you that they\'re all doing something a little different.',
